#: {{synonyms|en|Cel-Liberation Day|Emancipation Day|Freedom Day|Jubilee Day}}
#* {{quote-journal|en|title=Local news|newspaper=Brenham Weekly Banner|location=Brenham, Tex.|publisher=J[ohn] G. Rankin|date=25 June 1891|volume=XXVI|issue=26|page=&#91;7&#93;|pageurl=https://www.newspapers.com/image/68044659|column=1|oclc=14369205|passage=There was{{sic|were}} not so many colored people in the city as usual on Saturday evening, all of them, very near, being out at the "'''Juneteenth''' siliibration."}}
#* {{quote-journal|en|title=Watermelons are Moving|journal=Fruit Trade Journal and Produce Record|location=New York, N.Y.|publisher=Fruit Trade Journal Company|date=15 June 1912|volume=XXXXVII|issue=10|page=12|pageurl=https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=uiug.30112106851220&view=1up&seq=180|oclc=9295677|passage=If there is plenty of sunshine within the next ten days there will be sufficient supply of watermelons in Southwest Texas to take care of the "'''Juneteenth'''" celebrations of San Antonio's colored population.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|author=Julia Walcott Hoffman|chapter=I|title=Pearl o’ Great Price or A Woman’s ’Sperience|location=Chicago, Ill.|publisher=Gift and Music Shop|year=1921|page=11|pageurl=https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=nnc1.1000026522&view=1up&seq=23|oclc=39069637|passage="'Twere '''Juneteenth''' day," she began reverentially, "when my light firs' broke. The darkies all bunched up down in the live oak grove were a-singin' an' a-dancin', 'spressin' their glory 'cause they warnt no mo' slaves nohow.["]}}
#* {{quote-book|en|author=Hubert Anthony Shands|chapter=VIII|title=White and Black|location=New York, N.Y.|publisher=[[w:Harcourt (publisher)|Harcourt, Brace and Company]]|year=1922|page=50|pageurl=https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=uc1.$b312484&view=1up&seq=58|oclc=791788|passage="But whut if it rains?" asked Josy. "It always do rain on '''Juneteenth'''." / "Dat's jes' de way of it," said John. "Someone is always a-th'owin' cold water on eve'ything I does."}}
#* {{quote-book|en|author=J. Frank Davis|chapter=Episode I. Juneteenth and Joada|title=Almanzar Evarts, Hero|location=Macon, Ga.|publisher=J. W. Burke Company|year=1925|pages=13–14|pageurl=https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=uc1.$b799036&view=1up&seq=20|oclc=2199617|passage=He had invited her to attend the '''Juneteenth''' picnic as his guest all day. And now he had done something that never, in all his life, had he heard of any colored boy doing before—planned an expensive outing right on the eve of the big annual event. [...] "'''Juneteenth'''"—white people also pretty generally use the phrase—is their Emancipation Day, and it is the one day in the year when every Caucasian is supposed to consider the comfort and enjoyment of his negro friends ahead of his own.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|author=J[ohn] Mason Brewer|authorlink=J. Mason Brewer|chapter=Juneteenth|editor=[[w:J. Frank Dobie|J[ames] Frank Dobie]]|title=Tone the Bell Easy|series=Publications of the Texas Folk-lore Society|seriesvolume=no. 10|location=Austin, Tex.|publisher=[[w:Texas Folklore Society|Texas Folk-lore Society]]|year=1932|pages=8–54|pageurl=https://muse.jhu.edu/chapter/2471788|oclc=1904196|passage=Truck drivers, business men, and school teachers belonging to the racial group have told me tales, but the best of tale-tellers has been some ex-slave buoyed up by the spirit of a Nineteenth of June celebration—the "'''Juneteenth'''"—the day on which all colored people in the South commemorate the freedom of their race from slavery. The significance of the day is so great and the tales I have collected are so bound up with the legalized slavery which, in 1865, this day put an end to, that I have used '''''Juneteenth''''' as a title. Nobody who does not understand a '''Juneteenth''' celebration can ever understand the Negro or his songs and tales.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|author=Writers’ Program, [[w:Works Progress Administration|Work Projects Administration]], Texas|chapter=Folklore and Folkways|title=Texas: A Guide to the Lone Star State|series=American Guides Series|location=New York, N.Y.|publisher=Hastings House|year=1940|year_published=1943|section=part I (Texas: Yesterday and Today)|page=97|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=RmS4RIl4W-AC&pg=PA97|oclc=479997144|passage=The annual celebration by Negroes of June 19—the day when emancipation from slavery became effective in the State [...]—is general; few Texas Negroes would consider working on "'''Juneteenth'''" if it can be avoided. The holiday is generally observed by a picnic at which everyone eats, dances and sings to his heart's content.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|author=William H. Wiggins, Jr.|chapter=Following the Freedom Trail|title=O Freedom!: Afro-American Emancipation Celebrations|location=Knoxville, Tenn.|publisher={{w|University of Tennessee Press}}|year=1987|year_published=2000|page=5|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=5qr8cRUJC-cC&pg=PA5|isbn=978-0-87049-520-5|passage=As I chewed on my extra-hot barbecue sandwich, Mr. Artis Lovelady, the vendor and celebration sponsor, explained why he was having a '''Juneteenth''' observance: "I just wanted to do something, just wanted to kinda bring back old times and let the younger people see what we used to do to celebrate it on account of our Emancipation Proclamation."}}
#* {{quote-book|en|author=Michael Kammen|authorlink=Michael Kammen|chapter=The Civil War Remembered—but Unreconciled|title=Mystic Chords of Memory: The Transformation of Tradition in American Culture|edition=1st Vintage Books|location=New York, N.Y.|publisher={{w|Vintage Books}}|year=1991|year_published=February 1993|section=part 2 (Circa 1870 to 1915)|page=122|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=CyQF6pKZ61YC&pg=PA122|isbn=978-0-679-74177-0|passage=But what they [black people] chose to emphasize by means of traditional activities each year was the memory of gaining freedom. Consequently in African-American communities, especially in the South, a day of prayer, preaching, and festivities usually known as "'''Juneteenth'''" came to be observed [...].}}
#* {{quote-book|en|author=Ralph Ellison|authorlink=Ralph Ellison|chapter=7|editor={{w|John F. Callahan}}|title=[[w:Juneteenth (novel)|Juneteenth: A Novel]]|location=New York, N.Y.|publisher={{w|Random House}}|year=1999|page=131|pageurl=https://archive.org/details/juneteenthnovel00elli/page/131/mode/1up|isbn=978-0-394-46457-2|passage=There's been a heap of '''Juneteenths''' before this one and I tell you there'll be a heap more before we're truly free!}}
#* {{quote-book|en|author=W[illiam] Fitzhugh Brundage|authorlink=W. Fitzhugh Brundage|chapter=Celebrating Black Memory in the Postbellum South|title=The Southern Past: A Clash of Race and Memory|location=Cambridge, Mass.; London|publisher=The Belknap Press of {{w|Harvard University Press}}|year=2005|page=55|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=gNur7ykIk0sC&pg=PA55|isbn=978-0-674-01876-1|passage=On June 19, 1883, an eighteen-gun salute on the plaza in front of the Alamo in San Antonio, Texas, signaled the start of the annual '''Juneteenth''' observance.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|author=Thad Sitton|author2=James H. Conrad|chapter=Saturday Nights and Sunday Mornings|title=Freedom Colonies: Independent Black Texans in the Time of Jim Crow|series=Jack and Doris Smothers Series in Texas History, Life, and Culture|seriesvolume=no. 15|location=Austin, Tex.|publisher={{w|University of Texas Press}}|year=2005|page=105|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=O_v9DAAAQBAJ&pg=PA105|isbn=978-0-292-70618-7|passage=Proud Pelham in Navarro County had a long history of major '''Juneteenths'''. Every year on June 19, pigs and goats roasted over open pits or old bedsprings, while fish deep-fried in lard in big washpots hung from trees.}}
#* {{quote-hansard|en|speaker=[[w:Lena Taylor|Lena C. Taylor]]|title=Announcements, Adjounment Honors, and Remarks under Special Privilege|report=State of Wisconsin Senate Journal: Ninety-ninth Regular Session|house={{w|Wisconsin State Senate}}|location=|publisher=|date=17 June 2009|volume=|page=218|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=f3AjAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA218|column=2|passage=Senator Taylor, with unanimous consent, asked that when the Senate adjourn, it do so in honor of "'''Juneteenth''' Day," to symbolize the struggle for freedom and equality in the United States. [...] Indeed, '''Juneteenth''' Day is much more about the future than the past. It is a day where we gather to continue the struggle. We all realize the true freedom still eludes many of us.}}

